ca 1390","1385":"1385","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","after 16 July 1419":"na 16 juli 1419","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1390":"1390","1356":"1356","ABT 1385":"circa 1385","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1475":"1475","1442":"1442","1419":"1419","Felbrigg, Norfolk, England":"Felbrigg, Norfolk, England","Playford, Suffolk, England":"Playford, Suffolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of,Tuttington,Norfolk,England":"Tuttington, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Tuttington, Norfolk, England":"Tuttington, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1356–after 16 July 1419":"1356–after 16 July 1419","1356–1419":"1356–1419","1345–1400":"1345–1400","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1372–1442":"1372–1442","1385–Male":"1385–Deceased","1390–1475":"1390–1475","1395–Male":"1395–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","about 1390":"about 1390","1385":"1385","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","after 16 July 1419":"after 16 July 1419","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1390":"1390","1356":"1356","ABT 1385":"about 1385","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1475":"1475","1442":"1442","1419":"1419","Felbrigg, Norfolk, England":"Felbrigg, Norfolk, England","Playford, Suffolk, England":"Playford, Suffolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","of,Tuttington,Norfolk,England":"Tuttington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Tuttington, Norfolk, England":"Tuttington, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":26,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Margery de Aspale was born in 1356, in Tuttington, Norfolk, England as the daughter of de Aspale. She married George Felbrigg in 1372, in Tuttington, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died after 16 July 1419, and was buried in Playford, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1356–after 16 July 1419":"1356–pärast 16. juulit 1419","1356–1419":"1356–1419","1345–1400":"1345–1400","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1372–1442":"1372–1442","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1390–1475":"1390–1475","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1385":"1385","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","after 16 July 1419":"pärast 16. juulit 1419","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1390":"1390","1356":"1356","ABT 1385":"umbes 1385","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1475":"1475","1442":"1442","1419":"1419","Felbrigg, Norfolk, England":"Felbrigg, Norfolk, England","Playford, Suffolk, England":"Playford, Suffolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of,Tuttington,Norfolk,Engla